The Count's wife, Madame de Merret, died in her sleep in her bed at the Chateau of Châlons-Drouot, France, in 1848. The author has never met the Count, but has heard stories of his wife's many lovers and of his love for the Count. He tells how the Count took a diamond from his wife, and gave it to him as a present. He also tells how he bought an "Imitation of Christ" lamp and a chair for his wife for her bed.
